Feb 8 2009 	Great location great value	We gave ourselves a $200/night budget for our stay in San Francisco, and we wanted a great location downtown and a nice, comfortable hotel. Everyone told us how expensive San Francisco is and everyone thought we were crazy, but everyone was wrong. With the economy in a tailspin, there are some great hotel bargains to be had, and the Powell Hotel is one of the best. Even including the valet parking charge (which I thought was high but which I later found out was the same price we would have paid had we parked in a garage ourselves), we paid about $100 per night, and the Powell was worth every penny.The Powell is amazingly well-situated downtown, just a couple blocks from Union Square and with the cable car turnaround literally just outside the lobby door -- additional buses and trolleys stop just outside, as well -- so it's perfect for seeing the sites, and there are restaurants and shops galore within blocks -- something for every taste and every budget. It's also pretty easy to get to but was devilishly hard to find, even with our GPS.It's not what I'd call a &quot;luxury&quot; hotel, but the Powell does have class and a certain undeniable elegance. It's an old place, and the wood floors are creaky, but the rooms are nicely updated and the whole hotel is impeccably clean. The service was first-rate, from the housekeeping staff to the valet (amazingly quick) to the front desk attendants, who were eager to help and give advice and who even made an unreasonably large number of copies for me absolutely free of charge just to make up for some minor problems I had printing out some documents. In regaling our friends with our San Francisco chronicles I've described our room as postage-stamp size, but my girlfriend vehemently disagrees with this appraisal, so let's just say it was not a large room, but we certainly didn't feel cramped.All in all the Powell far exceeded our expectations, and we'd stay there again in a heartbeat the next time we're in San Francisco.	
