Nov 3 2007 	Disappointed by Powell	I recently stayed in the Powell hotel when it was selected as an &quot;overflow&quot; hotel for a recent conference. The lobby was fairly well decorated, and the front desk staff was friendly despite shirts that very clearly needed to be pressed. To be fair, I don't remember exactly how the reservation was worded, but I recall booking 2 beds. My assumption was that there would be 2 full beds. In fact, there were 2 twin beds. The renovations were quite disappointing. Years of painting on top of layers of paint have resulted in very poor paint finishes -- puffy due to too many layers in sections, with doors that are painted so poorly that brush strokes were often clearly visible. Carpeting in the hallways appeared new, but looked cheap as did the faux wood flooring that was interspersed with the new carpeting. According to the front desk staff, the ice machine was broken during my stay (they only mentioned one on the 3rd floor, while it is possible that there were others, they weren't mentioned). My room was particularly unpleasant ,and it is the reason for my rating of 2 stars vs. 3. The paint in the rooms was bubbling and peeling in areas, particularly by the radiator which appeared to me to be the only way to heat the room (VERY noisy). Additionally, the noise out front of the hotel was a problem. Although the proximity to the cable cars is quaint, the near-constant bells and noises are distracting and interfere with attempts to work in your room. The carpeting in my room was disgusting in places and resembled the pictures of stained carpeting posted by others (I did not photograph my room). The bathroom was large and stocked with the basics, although the grout between tiles was discolored and in some places chipped. There appeared to have been no attempt to decorate the bathroom which was totally white except some peach-colored tile around the bathtub. The cleaning staff did an admirable job each day attempting to clean a room that was well past its prime. Towel and amenities were restocked daily. I wish that I had photographed my room to show readers more clearly the details to which I am referencing; however, rest assured that my room did not resemble some of the nicer rooms photographed by other travelers. It is possible that renovation efforts had not reached my floor (?) although the hallways looked complete.	
Oct 13 2007 	Location Location Location	A friend and I stayed at the Powel Hotel based on research of reviews on Tripadvisor. I found the positive reviews informative and accurate. Aside from the very reasonable rates for a San Francisco hotel, the number one plus for the Powell is location, location, location! Located at the Powell and Market BART station, access to and from the airport is very convenient (roundtrip fare $10.30). Other points in the Bay Area are also easily reached from here via BART. The Powell is also at the terminating point for the streetcar line going to Fisherman's Wharf and on Market one can catch the MUNI to the Embarcadero or the Castro. If you plan to use public transportation I would recommend purchasing a MUNI pass. The three day pass is $18.00 and gives you unlimited access. Since a oneway fare on the streetcar is $5.00 you can see how this could be a real money saver.The Powel itself is a quaint, clean and courteous establishment. I have stayed in much higher rated hotels in San Francisco in the past, but for the money and location the Powell, in my opinion, ,just can't be beat.	
