Jun 24 2007 	Location has TWO meanings!	I just returned from a stay at the Powell. I want to open by saying that I have never stayed in a &quot;5-star&quot; hotel, but have stayed at many &quot;nice&quot; places right here in Vegas. (TI, Ceasars, Luxor etc) The location of the hotel can't be beat. We flew into Oakland, and took the BART system and seriously ended up just steps from the front door of the hotel. As many have mentioned, the cable cars are right out the front door and we used them a lot to get to the wharf. We stayed in a double room and it looked just like the photo on the website of a double room. They are not very large, but my wife, myself, and our two kids (8 and 12) did fine. It is a very old building, but I kind of thought that added to the place. The room was clean, and the beds were fine. We were out of the hotel most days for 12+ hours each day, so it was basically a place to sleep. This brings us to the reason that I say location has two meanings......we were in room 301 which is right above the cable car turnaround. It is LOUD! I would highly recommend that you bring earplugs as the cable cars go until after 12:30 at night and fire back up at 6:00 in the morning. Between the constant &quot;ding ding&quot; of the bells and the multitude of street performers playing any and all types of instruments (some not so well) just outside your window, it gets old. If you need a view (which was nice) bring earplugs. If a view isn't important, then press them early on for a room away from Powell Street. From the hotel, we were able to walk to many places including Union Square and China Town. (When walking to China town, walk over to Grant street and then up to China town. There is very little climb compared to trying to go up Powell and then down on California....VERY steep) We bought the CityPass and it was GREAT! I was a bit skeptical about the places that you get to see, but each and every place on the list was a first class establishment all the way. You can walk to the aquarium and the San Fran Museum of Modern Art right from the hotel, and the included MUNI system passes allow you to take busses/trolley/cablecars to the others for free. If you have kids, I can't tell you enough that the CityPass is a great investment. We were only there for 4 days and to really do a good job of seeing all of the places included in the CityPass, a couple of more days would have been nice as we felt a bit rushed at a couple of them. Overall, if you plan on spending a bunch of time at the hotel, this probably isn't the place for you. If, however, you need an inexpensive (we payed under $100 per night through hotels.com) place just to lay your head at night, this is a good option. It is by no means a fancy place, but it is decent and serves its purpose. As an added note, DO NOT walk out the &quot;back&quot; door of the hotel and continue into the &quot;tenderloin&quot; district. We walked about 2-3 blocks that direction, and it is NOT a place you want to be with your family. My wife was white with fear, and my kids eyes were the size of a medium pizza. It is a very scary area just a few blocks away, but the area at the hotel is fine and full of tourists.	
