Oct 29 2006 	Couldn't wait to leave!	My husband and I had planned to stay at the Powell in San Francisco for 4 nights. We ended up staying only one night and got out of there asap. We booked our &quot;standard room&quot; on hotels.com under the understanding that it was a double or queen bed. When we got there, the guy at the (very messy) front desk told us that they didn't have that room, and we'd have to stay in a room with two twin beds. My husband is 6'6&quot;, so that wasn't going to fly. I had read about the renovated rooms on this site, so I asked for one, and the guy said he didn't have any. We told them we were going to find another hotel in the area, and all of a sudden they had a queen room available for us. So we went to the queen room, which was very old but had new carpet and new bed linens. The window looked out into a small concrete shaft with exhaust fans in it and faced a few feet away from other room windows. The bathroom was very old but appeared clean. Within the first 5 minutes of being in the bathroom, a VERY LARGE COCKROACH crawled out from the wall near the toilet and joined us. We called the front desk and within a few minutes someone came up and picked up the cockroach and flushed it down the toilet. The guy who cleaned it up (maintenence guy?) told us that now he was going to get in trouble. He moved us to yet another room, which was one of the renovated rooms we had asked for in the first place. The renovated room was nice and felt more secure than the older room. It also didn't have any holes in the walls for roaches to crawl out from. We got out of there the next morning and spent the rest of our trip at the downtown Marriott which was so very much cleaner.In summary:The only good thing about the Powell is the location. You cannot get a better location than this... it is directly next to all public transportation you could possibly need, plus in walking distance to museums, restaurants, shopping, etc. If you can get one of the renovated rooms, they're better, but the front desk is sure to give you the runaround and try to give you an old room first.Bad things- cockroaches, dirty old room, shady service. I would NEVER stay at the Powell again. If you're staying there, bring your flip-flops and don't sleep with your mouth open!!!	
Sep 30 2006 	Surprisingly Great Little Hotel	I was meeting some friends in SF and they had already booked rooms at the Powell. I did the same, so that hanging out would be easier, but I expected the hotel to be a dump. Surprise surprise, it was quite nice.I paid $96 a night plus $34 for valet parking (overpriced, but you're paying for convenience - parking garages in the area charge $20-27/night). I tend to spend about $150/night plus parking when I stay in SF, and often the cleanliness and quality of the rooms at the price are not that great. So you can see why I thought the Powell would be a dump at $96/night.I was asked on check in if I wanted a low-floor or a high-floor. I requested a high-floor. People who chose to stay in low floors and complain about the noise are crazy. You're in the middle of the City. Of course there's going to be noise when you're 30 feet from one of the main throughfares (Market St.) and you decide to be on a low floor.The room was small but more than adequate for one person. There was room for the queen bed, a chair in the corner, a low dresser with the television on it, two night stands and still there was plenty of space to walk around the bed. The bathroom was also on the small-ish size, but 2 people could have been in there at the same time with no problem.The room was furnished very nicely. The sheets were clean and of very good quality, the comforter was wrapped in a sheet, which was great, and the pillows were super comfy. The room also had old-fashioned arcitectural features, such as beautiful crown-molding. The closet had nice wooden hangers and there were about 12 of them, which was very useful.it's true that there was no air-conditioner in the room, but that's pretty standard for SF. Very few homes in the City have air-conditioning because it's rarely hot enough to need AC. A ceiling fan would have been nice, but I stayed absolutely comfortable during my time in the room by opening or closing the window if I got cold or warm. A novel concept, I realize, but it works.The staff were very nice and helpful. The location is great for most tourists - Powell cable cars are literally outside the door, plenty of palces to eat within a 3 block radius, BART station to get to the airport or the East Bay are 1/2 block away and Union Square shopping is 3 blocks away. Of course, this is also downtown San Francisco, so there are plenty of homeless folks, some of which are mentally ill and/or high, traffic is wretched during commute times and some of the surrounding areas are marginal. But that's urban life.Overall, I would most definitely stay at the Powell again. I was extremely pleased with the quality and the value of the hotel.	
