Jun 8 2006	All right for a budget hotel	My husband and I stayed at the Powell for our last night in California. We chose it for the location. We wanted to be near the cablecar and the BART (so that we would at least have the option of taking it back to the airport). We knew it was a budget hotel so we didn't have high hopes and it was pretty much what we expected. Our room was pretty small and had a musty smell. We opened the window which overlooked some type of little courtyard and looked directly into the windows of the rooms across from us. The window screen had a huge gash in it. There was no a/c so it was a good thing we stayed there early in the summer. The bathroom was small but adequate for one night. We had to wait for several minutes for the hot water to heat up before taking showers. We arrived at 11:00 a.m. and were able to check into our room right away. That was a pleasant surprise. The front desk clerk was friendly but not very helpful. We saw signs that the Bay Bridge was going to be closed on Sunday so we needed to figure out the best way to get to Oakland Airport. Because we had a lot of luggage we wanted to take a shuttle rather than the BART. When we asked the front desk clerk about making arrangements for transportation to the airport she told us that BART was the only way to get there. She said there were no taxis or shuttles running to Oakland. This really didn't make sense to us so we called and were able to book a shuttle. She tried to be helpful but she should have made sure she knew what she was talking about before giving us advice. The location was great. Since it was the last day of our vacation, we had a lot of last-minute sightseeing to do and it was a perfect spot to begin and end. The cablecar turnaround was right outside the door. There were a lot of homeless people around the hotel begging for money but that's expected in a big tourist area. It wasn't the best hotel and I would prefer to stay somewhere a little nicer but you can't beat the location.	
May 17 2006	Good deal Nice Place	Stayed 5/5 through 5/11...Great location...Very good value for the price. This is not 4 star luxury, but a clean, comfortable place to crash after exploring the great city of San Francisco. The interior had an old-time San Fran feeling to it. I liked the vintage photos of the hotel and cable cars in our room. Our room was directly above the cable car turn-around, probably the noisiest spot in the place, and save for the night they power-washed the turn-around(whch only lasted an hour or so), we never had a problem with noise. This is a major, bustling metropolis, so if your expecting rural quietude, then you should not have decided to come here for a vacation. I was amused by people complaining about noise. It's not Ottumwa, Iowa, folks.The people were all very friendly and helpful, the place was clean, and we enjoyed our stay immensely. The other complaints all seemed silly to me, because San Fran is not a place you would go to so you can stay in your hotel and relax. We were out and about every day, and usually came home nice and tired (and full from the great restaurants).The neighborhood is bustling (two blocks from Union Square-tons of shopping, eating, drinking options). There are street people around, and they panhandle, but at no time did it seem unsafe. I would recommend this place if you are value conscious, active, and enjoy being in the heart of the action in a great city.	
