Oct 23 2005	Just fine for the price	We (myself, wife and adult daughter) stayed in Room 501 overlooking Powell Street and the cable car turn-around over the Labour Day weekend. The room was large, high ceiling, with two queen beds, coffee maker and a clean (but a bit old fashioned) bathroom. Good supply of fluffy towels and soap/shampoo. Beds were comfy and clean. The staff we met were fine (Brenda in particular) - but we didn't have too much to do any others as we out of the hotel from early morning to midnight! There is a safety deposit box system in operation behind the reception desk (losing the key will cost you $300!!). The coffee bar is very small but okay if you want to carry something back to the room. There's plenty of eateries nearby, so no food problem.No air conditioning in our room so consequently the only 'problem' we had was the traffic noise - the &quot;ding-de-ding&quot; sound from the cable cars arriving and departing at the turn-around is etched into our brains. But as we were on vacation it didn't matter. It'd be much different if the guest was on a business trip. The hotel is perfectly located just a few steps from Market Street BART and many bus/tram/trolly car routes. There is a very useful Visitors Centre down the escalators at the BART Station with all the maps and info you'll ever need. It is a short walk (2 blocks) up Powell St to Union Square.We would stay there again without hesitation. We booked thru Expedia and got a reasonable discount, so we got good value for money. It is important to remember that this is an old city centre building and they have done the best they can with it.uncletony and family	
Sep 11 2005	Great budget hotel and no mice!	Just returned from SFO and our stay at the Powell Hotel. We were very pleased with this hotel. We took the BART from the airport. Luggage was not a problem, as I had worried it would be. You really do pop out just a few steps from the hotel. We bought the 3 day pass for the cable car and Muni and it was so conveniet to take these to and from the front door of the hotel. When we checked in we asked for a renovated room and were given one. The room had no view, as it was an inside room, but that was okay with us. The room was also tiny. But we were in our room very little so it didn't matter. Room was clean and attractive. The bed was very comfortable. The brochure states that they supply bathrobes, bottled water and bathroom scales, but we never saw any of that. The coffee shop downstairs was good and the prices were reasonable, but with the time change, we were up at 5 or 6Am and the shop did not open until 7:30. I have to mention that the people of San Francisco are some of the most helpful people anywhere. Several times we were overheard wondering aloud about directions, or how to buy BART tickets, which train to get on, etc. and we were volunteered assistance. That was a pleasant surprise. Be prepared for homeless people and beggars everywhere. It is sad. Sometimes we gave and sometimes not. If you don't have terribly high standards, you should be pleased with Hotel Powell. It is a good value. We used Expedia and got a lower rate than the hotel direct.	
Sep 7 2005	Loved my Labor Day Weekend at the Powell!	My girlfriend and I just returned from a labor Day weekend in SFO. This was our first time to SFO for both of us and I was so nervous about picking the right place. I stayed here based on forum comments and reviews. I booked directly with the hotel after searching travel websites. The savings were minimal by using a travel website and you are not guaranteed your room size . ( As we were checking out there was a family of 6 who were stuck with 2 single rooms because they booked through Hotels.com). The staff was very friendly and we received smiles throughout from all staff. We asked for more pillows and they were delivered promptly with a smile.The rooms are small compared to the suites at The Venetian in Vegas, but more than adequate for the 2 of us and our luggage, etc. We were not cramped for space at all. The bathroom had modern fixtures and was very clean. The elevators were quick and safe, and the front desk was very helpful. They were happy to provide any assistance we needed. Excellent!LOCATION LOCATION LOCATION! You do not need to rent a car while staying here. Jump on the BART from the airport, $5.00 gets you to the door of the hotel. Ok, you have to go up the escalator and cross a small square (trolley turnaround) but it couldn't be any easier. If you are concerned with taking luggage on the BART as we were, don't be. There is plenty of room on the BART and it wasn't a hassle at all. You have streetcars in front of the hotel (like the F line to the Embarcadero, Pier 39 and Fisherman's Wharf) and the famous trolley cars right in front of the door. It is so convenient!Buy yourself a Muni pass for $9.00 a day or $18 for a 3 day. The trolley is $5.00 each way otherwise so you can see how this pays for itself. By the way, we felt safe on all transportation even at midnight from Fisherman's Wharf, BART included.I will definitely go back to SFO and I will DEFINITELY stay at the Powell again. By the way, my girlfriend loved the hotel, loved the location and ease of getting around. She was impressed with my choice of hotels for our first stay in SFO.	
Sep 5 2005	It's Not Just the Location	Like the other reviewers here I chose this hotel based on its great location. Literally just off the escalator from the Powell St. BART station and with the Powell St. cable car turnaround at their doorstep public transportation is so convenient. Take BART from the airport and you'll have no need to rent a car and hassle with hills and parking if you're just touring the city. Buy a 1, 3 or 7-day Muni Passport and a transit map at the cable car ticket booth so that you don't have to hassle with finding change for fare. Going to a Giants game? Just hop on the N-Judah Muni Metro at the BART station and you'll be at the ballpark in minutes.But, it's not just the location that makes this a good choice for your SF stay. The staff was extremely friendly and helpful. Yes, it's an old hotel, but I've stayed in other old hotels in SF and the quality and cleanliness of this hotel meets or exceeds those. The furnishings, carpet and bathroom were clean and in good working order. My son was disappointed that they didn't have the Cartoon Network on their cable service, but the TV was big and new.No on site restaurant, but many good ones a short walk away. The lobby snack bar has a good selection of pastries, fruit, juices and good coffee so that you can easily pick up a simple breakfast to get you started in the morning.I booked the room through the hotel website after comparing prices at the major travel websites. I didn't use Priceline for SF because there were three of us on this trip and knowing that many SF hotel rooms are tiny I needed to guarantee that we'd get a room with two double beds. (Priceline rates are for two people only) I should qualify my comments by saying that we were given a free upgrade to a Jr. Suite. I'm not sure what we did to deserve this, but it definitely added to our enjoyment of this hotel.	
