Mar 2 2005	You get what you pay for	We stayed in the Powell Hotel in mid January 2005. We asked to see the rooms before checking in and got one of the 'updated' rooms. The room was somewhat cramped, but who spends all their time in the room. The bathroom was very upscale. We checked in around 2 pm and toured the town during the day. Arriving back to our room, it was a bit chilly. I turned on the radiator, but two hours later, no heat. I went downstairs to check about the heat and was told that it is on only from 5 pm to 5 am. OK.....so I waited until 5 pm. Still no heat. I went downstairs and asked about it again and they gave me an electric heater and extra blankets. I guess it is routine to not have any heat. The five days that we stayed there, the electric heater was our only heat. I was glad it wasn't any colder! The hot water takes about 5 minutes to arrive; so plan ahead with showers. After returning home, I sent a letter to the manager of the Powell, asking about the lack of heat, but they did not respond.	
Feb 22 2005	Charming in Downtown SF	Really folks, you cannot find a better location for a hotel then The Powell Hotel. My wife and I landed in Oakland, took the BART minibus to Oakland Coliseum BART station, then a direct BART ride to Powell station. Up the stairs and we were right in the center of all the action. The Powell Hotel is right there when you walk up from the bART station. And so are other attractions you might be interested in. Shopping at places like Forever 21, GAP, Anthropologie, Virgin Megastore, Apple Store, Nordstrom (check out the twisting escalators inside), Abercrombie, Victoria Secret, and the list goes on. There is also Union Square 2 blocks north, Yerba Buena Gardens and Museum of Modern Art two blocks east, a miriad of dining and theatrical productions around and within easy walking distance. Impressive location for a hotel.You can buy a 1 day, 3 day, or 7 day pass at the SF cable car booth which allows you to ride the cable cars, MUNI bus system and F-Line trolley cars all over the place. We bought the 3 day pass for $15/person which was an awesome deal considering the cable cars are $3 one way/person alone. The bus system in SF is great and can get you any place you need to go. People on the MUNI buses are friendly and easy to get into conversations with making SF a place youd want to live. Down here in Los Angeles Id never ride the buses filled with illegals, gang members and generally people who for some reason cannot get a drivers license and a $500 car. Never ride the bus in L.A.!! About the hotel... my only complaint is that the room we stayed needed some restoration work (like new moulding around doorways, windows, etc), otherwise it was complete and very clean. Service was always friendly and the best part is they held our luggage even after we checked out, allowing us to spend our last day running around without having to carry our luggage. It was worth the $5 tip. If you need BRAND NEW furniture, fixtures, tiling, etc and are really concerned about things like that, maybe this place isnt right for you. For my wife and I it was perfect. The price and location made this an ideal setting. It was nice to have a room with a view overlooking Powell Sreet and watch the cable cars. The lines for the cable cars can get long and it was nice to look out the window to check! Again, great place to stay, great locale and reminded me of an apartment we rented when we were in Kiev, Ukraine overlooking Independence Square. We will definitely stay at the Powell again.	
Jan 20 2005	A Surprising Non-Descript Gem	Admittedly, my expectations of this place were quite low due to a few reasons: the lowly 2-star rating on the online hotel booking service, the less-than-impressive grainy photos on that website, and the relatively low rate of $72 (especially given the ultra-prime downtown &quot;close to everything&quot; location). We fully expected a somewhat shabby older hotel, but were willing to &quot;rough it&quot; for a short 2-nt stay in such an ideal location. It's a very easy-to-miss, non-descript, six-story building on a busy street. But...Upon entering the lobby, we were VERY pleasantly surprised at the lobby's pleasing contemporary decor and the welcoming attitude of the front desk. The nice guy asked our room preference and we decided on a street-facing room. (The hotel is bigger than it appears from the outside as there seems to be about 45 rooms on each floor--most do NOT face the street). Our room, 403, faced the cable car line, and while the charming clankedly-clank cable car bells do start to get annoying, the room was IMMACULATE. Yes, a bit smallish, but having stayed in dollhouse-like rooms in Europe and Hong Kong, it was more than just adequate. More importantly, the bathroom was sparkling, modernized, and supplied with the usual amenties such as shampoos, fresh, thick towels/cloths, and fragrant soaps. True, the bathroom walls were indeed thin as you can hear the folks thru the vent, but how long are you (or they for that matter) gonna be in the bathroom during an exciting trip to SF? Just close the bathroom door before retiring and you're fine. The king size bed, pillows and crisp linens were comfortable, iron/ironing board was supplied, working coffee maker, and carpeting wasn't stained and was well vacuumed. We saw no mice nor signs of any, contrary to what someone else posted in their review.Truthfully, I've stayed in everything from Le Meridiens and Doubletrees, to Motel 6s, and mom &amp; pop B &amp; Bs. Maybe we were just lucky this time and got a &quot;good&quot; room, but in terms of cleanliness, the Powell has, surprisingly, exceeded some Holiday Inns I've experienced (no exaggeration, either). The Powell may not be &quot;luxurious&quot; or &quot;posh&quot;, but it IS charming, CLEAN, the price is definitely right, the location is unmatched, and is more than adequate. Recommended.	
