Nov 14 2004	Great Hotel!	The staff at the Powell Hotel were very friendly and accommodating. We stayed there for 3 nights but for 2 of those nights, the staff moved us into one of their largest rooms. We had arrived late on Saturday night so we knew that we were going to get a small room with one double bed since they were fully booked. It was probably their smallest room since we didn't even have space for our luggage and we didn't have that much! After that first night we requested a larger standard room with 2 double beds and they did better than that! We got a suite with one queen bed with a walk in closet and a separate sitting room. It was very spacious and the staff even chose a room facing the quieter side of the city. It was a great deal as we still paid the standard room rate of $89 CDN / night for this larger suite!	
Nov 11 2004	Great expectations	Located in the heart of the city, but lacking in charm. Rooms were rather small and claustraphobic, lacking in storage space. Inner rooms which are quiter than street facing were dark and stifling. Staff were helpful and friendly enough. Advertises a coffee shop which does not exist anymore! Fortunately we had no car, but there are no facilities for parking. Okay for a short stay if you want the City, but consider something down at the Wharf instead. Beware of the horrendous amount of beggers in the City Centre!	
Nov 9 2004	Great Location but noisy and dirty	I stayed at this hotel with two girlfriends. There were three in our party so we asked for two beds. We were happy to find 3 full size beds in a one bedroom suite. The bad part was that the carpet had stains all over it and the walls were dirty. Also, when we stayed we heard people in the hall walking up the stairs which was very noisy. When someone would sneeze in a room next to us, it was like they were in the room. Watch out for the bums. They lock the doors at 7, so you will need a key to get in. One night a bum followed us in asking for money and the person at the front desk didn't say anything.The location is great since it's steps away from the bart station and shopping.	
Nov 3 2004	Excellent Location - Average Hotel	The location was perfect. Right next to the train station and right outside the front door is the cable car. The room had a heater which I don't think can be turned off from within the room which meant the room got quite warm. Fortunately when we stayed the weather was quite cold so we only needed to open the window for a few moments to cool the room down again.There was quite a lot of street noise, especially the rubbish trucks but they seemed to stop making noise after about 11:30pm. We couldn't hear any noise from the rooms next door but I'm not sure if anyone was even staying in them. The room did have a slight bad smell but the room and hotel was quite nicely decorated and seemed quite clean.At the time that we were staying quite a few other hotels had 'ex-'staff outside making clanging noises as some sort of union initiated protest. Fortunately there was none of this type of noise going on anywhere near this hotel.Some of the hotel staff were very friendly, some were not as approachable. Generally we had a slightly unsafe/uncomfortable feel but I can't pinpoint why we felt that way. I think that I would stay there again, mainly for the location but if I could find somewhere else that seemed better for the same sort of price I would probably try it out.	
Oct 31 2004	Noisy and coffeeless	I stayed in the hotel for 3 nights, having booked it through Expedia before leaving the UK. The reception was friendly, but the room was one of the smallest I think I have ever stayed in - though clean and tended by some pleasant Chinese chambermaids. The worst thing was trying to prepare a coffee! The coffee pot apparently did not fit the filter machine - which I only found out when the filter spilled water over the floor - oh, and all coffee, sugar and dried milk was damp and congealed in the packet. At night the noises in the corridor woke me twice after midnight, and it would appear that the room opposite mine was occupied by a hotel staff member (no swipe card machine on the outside, just a keyhole) who parked his bicycle in the corridor. I was put off (as were many English staying here) by the fact that the hotel locks its front door at 7pm (use your key to get in) to stop the vagrants getting in. A trip outside the hotel at 8pm meant running the gamut of large numbers of vagrants who continually ask for money, and can follow you down the street. I was only tempted to give money to one, who carried a board reading &quot;Dollars wanted for alcohol research&quot;.	
Oct 3 2004	Excellent Location friendly staff	We stayed at the Powell Hotel from September 11th to the 19th, 2004. It was perfect! It was very affordable. The rooms were clean and comfortable. The staff were very accomodating and helpful. The location could not have been better. The cable car stop begins and ends right outside the door of the hotel. All the shopping and restaurants were right around us, within walking distance. It even has a little café right in the building which was perfect for a light breakfast or quick snack. We felt safe in the area and would highly recommend it. Although there is no air conditioning (because it is not usually needed) you can request a fan which is more than sufficient since it never really gets that warm there.	
Sep 1 2004	Great Location Bad Smells	The Powell Hotel is situated in a great location, with shops, restaurants, and the trolley literally a few steps away, access to muni and bart is also nearby. The lobby of the hotel is quite nice and conveys that this place is dignified and contemporary and yet also historical. The customer service (very cordial hard workers) was excellent and the accomodations fair for the price we paid. Unfortunately, we did not have a great experience with our room. The room, #401, reeked of stale urine and the shower fixtures for hot and cold water were problematic. I would return to the Powell Hotel but not stay in #401.	
Aug 20 2004	Great charm and excellent location	After having stayed in San Francisco for about a week (at the end of April), we consider ourselves very fortunate to have found the Powell Hotel (we booked directly on their website - internet special of $89/night). I would certainly recommend the Powell Hotel for those looking for value, character and a great location.The Powell Hotel is wonderfully located about a 2 min walk from Union Square (nearly every shop you can think of is within a couple blocks) and about a 5 min walk to the Moscone Convention Centre (if you're there for a conference). Chinatown is only about a 5 minute walk. In fact, if you enjoy walking, and don't mind a few hills, you can walk up Powell Street to the water (e.g. Ghiardelli Square/Fisherman's wharf) in about 30 - 45 min. You can also walk down Market Street to the Ferry Building in about 20 min (no hills) --- Sausalito is only a short ferry ride across the Bay, and is a great little spot for lunch and wondering around.The cable car turnaround is right below the front of the hotel, but we certainly didn't consider it noisy even though our room was on the front of the hotel (mostly well behaved tourists waiting in line). This actually added to the unique experience and charm of the hotel. (The cable cars line-ups get busy at the turnaround, so walk up the street to one of the other stops to avoid the line). The rooms were clean, fresh and comfortable; not huge rooms, but certainly not cramped either. The housekeeping staff were quick to make up the rooms. We were in San Francisco during a unprecedented heat wave, and despite no air conditioning, the hotel provided fans which made it comfortable. The staff were very courteous and always helpful. The lobby is warm and welcoming, and has a modern art deco feel.There is also a great little cafe in the lobby, which was excellent for a quick breakfast (bagels, yogurt, coffee, etc). If you need to rent a car, nearly every major car rental company is within a block or two west of the Powell. This is great for getting out to Sonoma or Muir Woods and it's fairly easy to get in and out of San Francisco with a good map.If you're into running, a recommended route is to go from the Powell, down Market Street (nice wide sidewalk and flat) to the water (i.e. Ferry Building). From the Ferry Building, turn left and run down The Embarcadero. You can keep running along the Bay and turn around at any time. If you're into longer distances, keep running toward the Golden Gate (it's a little over an hour). We ran over the Golden Gate to Sausilito (about 2 hours) had breakfast, and took the ferry back....probably one of the most memorable experiences.The Cab fare is about $35 - $40 from the SFO airport. The Powell is not within the Tenderloin Area (i.e. the rougher part of San Francisco). In fact, there is a lot of security people around with all the shops and banks nearby as well as the BART (transit) security.	
Aug 1 2004 	What a steal - as long as you know what to ask for....	Wow! I must say I was a little scared about what I'd find with a room rate of $80 night (convention rate)...I normally stay at the W but am trying to be more careful with $$$ so decided to try the Powell. I was thrilled! Yes the rooms aren't going to win any design awards....but mine was very clean and the bathroom spotless. Was pleased to have the iron/board, cofee maker...Location was perfect for my needs and I can appreciate the urban feel. Definitely ask for a quiet room - I had 516 which wasn't huge, but noise wasn't a problem at all! Avoid 3rd floor - and even 4th if the room is above the vending area- it's really noisy. All the plusses mentioned already are true. I was told they have been renovating rooms which will be open soon. Sushi lovers make sure to go to the new sushi bar a block away - ask about it at the desk. Also, I found out as I was leaving they have a mezzanine with tables and chairs. I don't know if it will be turned into a restaurant but for now it would be a great place to hang out in lieu of your room. This is one of those hotels that isn't for everyone and I can certainly see how one could have a negative experience, but I think if you talk through your needs/requests at the time of reservation, you'll be quite pleased. And let me tell you, it was a treat to check out and not be handed a huge bill!	
Jul 30 2004	Great budget Hotel	I found out about Powell Hotel when i was searching in the internet for an hotel in San Francisco. I was amazed by the site. I've stayed a week in San Francisco at the Powell Hotel in May. It's a wonderful budget hotel, it's near everyhting and with a lot of transport options. The hotel staff were very friendly... and weren't expecting tips in return of favours... The room furniture was a little old, but the bathroom was renewed... i had a big bathroom. I left my heart in San Francisco and in Powell Hotel too:)	
Jul 29 2004	Great Location Great value	Four of us were there (two adult and two kids) from Monday July 12,2004 till Sunday July 18,2004Best location in the city without a doubt, steps from Powell Street BART station, cable cars and Union Square. Modern lobby with secured night entrance.Boutique hotel with older rooms but nicely decorated. Don't stay on the cable car side of the hotel if you are a light sleeper because they run till 12:30 AM and start operations at 6:00 AM. Staff were friendly and provided immediate service to a hot water problem (Too hot) we had in the bathroom	
Jul 26 2004	Good location clean but noisy	My wife and I stayed at the Powell for 4 nights the week of July 19. I spent hours searching the internet for the best price and reading reviews, and I decided on the Powell due to price, location, and photos. The hotel is old. The lobby is remodeled and very nice and the staff very friendly and helpful. Our room, however, was looking very old, but it was clean. The room was small, but for the price and location, it was fine. The biggest complaint was noise. The windows are only single pane, so ALL the street noise can be heard. This includes homeless people yelling after dark, cable cars, and traffic. To top it off, on two mornings we were awakend by a jackhammer below at 6:30 am. The second night we requested a floor fan to help drown out the noise. The front dest supplied it quickly and it greatly helped us to stand the noise and get a better nights sleep. Overall, the room was clean, staff friendly, price great (booked on Expedia), and location can't be beat. But just too noisy and the rooms could use a remodel. Parking can be pricey, too. I think that next time we would choose a hotel out of the downtown area, possible Cow Hollow.	
Jul 23 2004	Completely satisfied!	I spent hours reading reviews, researching room rates, etc. before settling on the Powell Hotel. We spent 4 nights there and had a terrific experience! The location is unbeatable in terms of public transport, shopping and eateries. The staff were all very friendly and helpful. The Powell is a cool old building, if you don't appreciate the beauty and quirkiness of historical buildings, don't stay here. Despite its age, our room was very clean and comfortable, which is all that matters. I will definately stay at the Powell when I return to SF, especially after the nearby construction is finished!	
Jul 16 2004	Terrible noisy room not that clean but good hotel location.	I stayed at the Poweel for three nights from 25th June 2004 on my way to Hawaii and for the Gay Pride weekend in SF. This was not my first time at the Powell but on the other occasion I had a much nicer room. I was given a twin bedded room with two single beds when I had requested a double through Expedia.. Okay fine this happenes sometimes on a busy weekend and they could not swap my room. However the room was right next to an ice machine that kept me awake clunking away all night. I know I paid a budget price but the rooms are in desperate need of renovation and are not that clean really. A place to stay if you want to be in a good location to get around the city but don't plan to spend more time in your room than when you are asleep.	
Jul 12 2004	The Powell Hotel - Misleading and disappointing	We just spent a weekend in San Francisco to shop and play. I booked a room with The Powell Hotel online using Expedia and after looking at the hotel's website and reading some reviews. The location and lobby of the hotel are great. It is right on Market across from Nordstrom. There is a nice espresso bar, efficient valet service, and the lobby was clean and newly furnished. The rooms are a different story. They are old and have a musty odor. The carpet was stained, the beds uncomfortable, and honestly, the bathroom had not been updated since the 60's. Our first room had a soggy wet spot outside of the bathroom and so we were moved into a room that looked the same but was dry. The room was $100 a night which may not be a lot in a big city but there must be better out there. Luckily, I brought my 15 year old niece and not my husband, because he would have thrown a fit and moved us!	
Jun 28 2004	Great Location - terrible smell !!!	We stayed here May 2004 for 3 days as part of a fly-drive around California. We chose this hotel as it was cheap, the location looked good and the reviews didn't seem too woeful. When you exit the hotel you are right at the start of the Powell tram line - excellent for a queue-less morning start. There were a couple of vagrants wandering around at night, but according to the hotel staff (who were very friendly and courteous), such problems have been much reduced of late, and we felt quite safe on the main street at night. There is a small coffee-shop in the lobby with bagels and such, but for a full breakfast you’ll have to go outside - there's plenty of choice, try the excellent upstairs diner just up the road. The room we got on the 6th floor was quiet, bright and large with a slightly dated but adequate décor and a large and comfortable bed. Now why didn’t we give this hotel a higher score ? It wasn’t because we never got a clear TV signal. What hit us when we entered our room was the strong mildew smell that permeated everything (it also didn’t help the general ambiance that someone had recently been sick in both lifts). The hotel staff were sympathetic, but another room they showed us on the 2nd floor was also smelly and was quite dark so, jetlagged as we were, we decided to chance it in the first room. They offered us a large fan (which made no difference), I left all the windows open during the day (which made no difference) but my trip was to the drug-store for a can of Ozium Air Sanitizer finally did kill off the worst of the smell (excellent stuff !). If you’re planning on staying in the Powell and they have the same crappy old carpets and musty smell I would highly recommend a trip to the drug store for a can of air freshener !	
Jun 16 2004	Amazing experience for travelers on a budget!	My husband and I, both students, couldn't believe the great hotel we snagged for $65/night on Expedia! The Powell has 1920s charm - from the wide staircases to the cosy rooms - that you just can't get at a Super 8, but it's still the same price! The location is amazing - just 25 steps from the nearest BART stop, plenty of shops and restaurants, and the trolley car turnaround. We requested a room overlooking the turnaround, where only pedestrians and trolleys are allowed to cross over the cobblestone street. So charming!!! The staff are friendly and helpful. The hotel closes its doors to everyone but guests after dusk to ensure adequate security. This was definitely a major plus in our first trip to San Francisco and we hope to visit again soon!	
Jun 4 2004	LEft my heart in the Powell	We stayed in San Francisco for three nights in september 2003. We had already booked a hotel there, but I was still surfing the net for hotels since that's one of my favourite activities. By accident I stumbled upon a great deal for the Powell Hotel. Stay two nights, get one free. I checked out the hotel and was surprised to find out it was the same place I stayed in in 1997. I booked without hesitation and I didn't regret it.The Powell Hotel is at a great location, just at the end of the cable car and next to a subway station. From there on, you can literally go anywhere in SF. We arrived in SF by air directly from Belgium and got dropped of at the hotel. We checked in, and the guy at the check-in (Gerry or Gary, can't remember) was really nice and helpful. He had a great sence of humour and treated us with a lot of respect. I immediately liked the guy. Without asking anything he gave us a map of the city and told us the places we should avoid. Very very helpful.Our room was in the back of the hotel and had no view at all. But I wasn't gonna complain. For the price we paid it was still a great deal. That place is awesome, since you wake up in the morning and you can hear the cable cars ringing. It's a wonderful sound to wake up to. Sure, the rooms are a little oldish, but they have charm. I'm already planning my US trip for next summer with my mom, and I'll make sure to stay at the Powell Hotel. 	
Jun 3 2004	Basic but great location	We stayed in the Powell for 4 nights recently and found the hotel to be very old fashioned although they were renovating it at the time so maybe now its not so bad! The staff were quite rude and unhelpful. The only saving grace was the location of the hotel. Right beside the BART stop (handy if coming straight from the airport). The hotel was also very close to plenty bars and shops. Despite everything I would stay here again. Suit budget holidaymakers.	
Jun 3 2004	Perfect for what we needed	I stayed at the Powell for 3 nights with two of my friends. We were looking to do a long weekend on a budget, and I think this met our needs perfectly!Like all the other reviews state, this is not a luxury hotel, but it is a clean, friendly hotel that positively added to our San Fransisco experience. The building, being a little older, had some excellent, old architecture, and just had a nice charm to it. We had a room with two double beds, and I felt it worked out fine for us, none of us felt cramped at all. Others have remarked on the friendly staff, and that is a very true statement. They seemed to go out of their way to help us with directions, or questions in general. We had a slight problem with our toilet one day, upon telling the staff, not only did they fix it very quickly, they gave us the key to the staff bathroom until they did fix it. Of course, one of the best things about this Hotel is it's location. It is literally steps away from the Trolley turnaround, for a novice to public transportation, this made it incredibly easy. If you don't mind walking it is only a few blocks away from Chinatown (about a 10 minute walk), and it is only two blocks away from Union Square, for shopping, and good restaurants. I would definitely stay here again, even if not planning a trip on a budget, just for the ambiance of the Hotel. 	
May 4 2004	Great location	Great location. Unfortunately, we were only there for one night. I wish we were able to stay longer. Didn't even need our own transportation, we took the Bart in from the Oakland airport and excited at the Powell station. The station was only an escalator away from the hotel. Very convenient!!! Rooms are on the smaller side, but are very clean. I would defenitely stay there again.	
May 4 2004	You get what you pay for	The Powell Hotel is a great location if you want to go to San Francisco and shop. There are literally hundreds of stores within the surrounding blocks. Coming from Chicago, this was not my idea of discovering a new city. The room was TINY and bathroom was small and old, everything smelled kind of funny. There is no AC, which probably isn't a problem most of the time, but we were there during a heatwave, and AC definitely would have made the stay nicer. There was also construction going on everyday, starting at 7am or so, and it was LOUD. The staff was really friendly and somewhat helpful (despite directing us into the Tenderloin to grab a bus at a urine-scented bus stop). Lobby was nice looking, furniture in room was outdated, tv was on a chintzy, wobbly stand. Locks on room doors didn't make me feel the safest. Great location for picking up public transportation, which we used the entire time we were there. The MUNI Passport is a great deal- letting you ride the buses, streetcars and cablecars for one price, and you don't have to deal with getting money out each time you get on a bus. I know I wouldn't stay here again, I'd definitely fork out the money to stay in a respected hotel chain next time. 	
